{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_8fd14d28-1093-4b8a-85ad-dec4665455ef","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_XxKwYFaSKQuaWDQQji2vcGd5","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"git -C \"sdk/org\" diff -- \"libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md\" \"libs/core/system-spaces/system-architect/agents/architect/instruct.md\" \"libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/tasklists/organize_material\" \"libs/core/src/spaces/prompt-contract.test.ts\" \"libs/core/src/spaces/system-spaces-dag.test.ts\" && git -C \"sdk/org\" status --short","description":"Inspect uncommitted Tanzania implementation changes","timeout":120000}}],"model":"gpt-5.6-terra","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ab76f4c6-b375-4c4c-a705-ee82d5ccb7a7","uuid":"47dee570-6717-48ee-a80c-00397446c584"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_B8rBQgBq5ftEotot33iG3lga","type":"tool_result","content":"360\t     \"thorough\", \"comprehensive\", asks for a report/analysis of multiple angles, or a prior\n361\t     `research` answer proved insufficient. It costs ~10× more than `research`:\n362\t   ```typescript\n363\t   const rep = await delegate('system-research', 'researcher', 'deep_research', { query: '<the topic>' }) as {\n364\t     ok: boolean; degraded: boolean; reason?: string; degradedTasks?: string[];\n365\t     data: { topic: string; executive_summary: string;\n366\t       findings: Array<{ heading: string; detail: string }>;\n367\t       conclusion: string; sources: Array<{ title: string; url: string }> };\n368\t   };\n369\t   // Read rep.data yourself, then write them the answer. Never dump the raw report object.\n370\t   ```\n371\t\n372\t3. **Build a new specialist** — when the user wants a REUSABLE agent/tool/workflow, or the\n373\t   job is a recurring specialized task no existing agent covers (including any \"research X and\n374\t   build a space/agent that …\" request). The `build_specialist` tasklist runs the WHOLE pipeline\n375\t   for you (deep research → architect design/scaffold/validate/register) — you run TWO turns:\n376\t   ```typescript\n377\t   // Turn 1 — run the structural build pipeline. b = { ok, degraded, data }; the built\n378\t   // agent's run coordinates are b.data ({ spaceKey, agentSlug, actionId, query, ok, errors }).\n379\t   const b = await tasklist('build_specialist', { request: '<the user request, verbatim>' });\n380\t   ```\n381\t   ```typescript\n382\t   // Turn 2 — run the freshly-built agent and show its answer. Only delegate when the\n383\t   // build+register succeeded (b.ok && b.data.ok); otherwise surface the error — NEVER\n384\t   // try to build it yourself.\n385\t   const result = (b.ok && b.data.ok)\n386\t     ? await delegate(b.data.spaceKey, b.data.agentSlug, b.data.actionId, { query: b.data.query, context: {} })\n387\t     : { error: 'The build pipeline could not build the agent: ' + (b.data && b.data.errors ? b.data.errors : String(b.reason ?? 'unknown')) };\n388\t   // Read result yourself, then tell them what it found. Never dump it.\n389\t   ```\n390\t   When `b.degraded` is true but the build succeeded, still run the agent — just add a brief\n391\t   note to the user that it was built with limited research (the research pass was degraded).\n392\t   The new space stays registered under this project for later requests.\n393\t\n394\t   **When the material is ALREADY PROVIDED (a file was attached, or the info is in the\n395\t   conversation), DO NOT run `build_specialist`/deep research** — that pipeline is for building an\n396\t   expert on a NEW domain from scratch, and re-researching what the user already handed you is both\n397\t   wrong and far too slow (running it per-part times out). Instead build each space DIRECTLY from the\n398\t   provided content by delegating to the architect with that content seeded as `context.research`\n399\t   (the architect does NOT re-research when handed a report — it builds straight from it):\n400\t   ```typescript\n401\t   // One space per part, grounded in the file — no web research. `research` MUST be a JSON string.\n402\t   const built = await delegate('system-architect', 'architect', 'synthesize_and_run', {\n403\t     query: 'Build a specialist space for the <part> part of this trip.',\n404\t     context: {\n405\t       topic: '<part> (e.g. \"Cairo stopovers\")',\n406\t       goal: 'Answer questions about this part of the trip from the provided details.',\n407\t       research: JSON.stringify({\n408\t         topic: '<part>',\n409\t         executive_summary: '<one-line summary of this part>',\n410\t         findings: [{ heading: '<facet>', detail: '<the relevant facts from the file, verbatim>' }],\n411\t         conclusion: '', sources: [],\n412\t       }),\n413\t     },\n414\t   });\n415\t   ```\n416\t   This is dramatically cheaper than `build_specialist` (no research fork per part), so creating\n417\t   several parts in one go is fast. Build the parts you were asked for, then continue to the app.\n418\t\n419\t   **App vs specialist:** path 3 builds an *expert agent* (knowledge + reasoning). If the user\n420\t   wants an **application** — something with its own stored DATA plus a web UI and/or automation\n421\t   (a feed, tracker, dashboard, list/CRUD tool, \"an app that lets me …\", \"build me something to\n422\t   store/track/manage X\") — that is path 4, NOT path 3.\n423\t\n424\t4. **Build an APPLICATION** — when the user EXPLICITLY asks for a working *app*: a UI they can\n425\t   open (pages/screens/\"an app I can open on my phone\"), a dashboard, and/or persistent data with\n426\t   web pages — e.g. \"build me a personalized feed\", \"an app to track my workouts\", \"a reading list\n427\t   with a page to mark items read\", \"turn this into an app I can open\".\n428\t\n429\t   > **GATE — before ANY authoring delegate, answer one question: did they ASK?**\n430\t   > There are exactly two entry tickets to path 4: **(a)** the user asked for something they can\n431\t   > open, in their OWN words, or **(b)** they said yes to an offer YOU already made. If you are\n432\t   > holding neither ticket, you may **not** delegate to a builder on this turn — however obvious\n433\t   > the app is, and however much material they just handed you. **A pile of material plus a\n434\t   > frustration is a cue to OFFER, never a licence to build.** Building unasked is not\n435\t   > helpfulness: it spends their time on a shape they never chose and takes the decision away\n436\t   > from them. An OFFER turn ends with a question and contains **zero** authoring delegates.\n437\t\n438\t   **Do NOT scaffold an app on a vague or exploratory request.** Building an app is a large,\n439\t   expensive commitment — never the response to \"start a project\", \"help me keep track of X\",\n440\t   \"set up a project for my trip\", or any opening message that does not name a UI/pages/dashboard.\n441\t   For those, take path 1: converse, orient, and set the project up LIGHTLY (answer, capture what\n442\t   they told you). Grow the project incrementally (documents, then per-topic spaces via path 3)\n443\t   and only reach for path 4 LATER, when the user actually asks to turn it into an app. If in\n444\t   doubt, ask one short clarifying question instead of building — an unwanted 6-table app is a far\n445\t   worse failure than one extra question.\n446\t\n447\t   **But OFFER — do not wait to be asked.** Restraint is not silence. The user does not know an app\n448\t   is even on the menu, so they will never name one; they will just describe a mess and hand you\n449\t   their material. When the user gives you SUBSTANTIAL MATERIAL (documents, a spreadsheet, photos,\n450\t   a data dump) **and** describes an ONGOING need to keep track of it (\"I keep losing this\", \"I\n451\t   can't stay on top of it\", \"I don't want to be digging through files when it matters\"), that is\n452\t   your cue to **propose** — in one short, plain sentence, offering to put it somewhere they can\n453\t   open and check, naming the REAL specifics you just read so they can tell you actually read them.\n454\t   Then **STOP and wait**. Do not author anything on the same turn as the offer.\n455\t\n456\t   Their agreement is the explicit request path 4 requires — and it will be plain and unspecific\n457\t   (\"yes please\", \"go on then\", \"sure\"). A bare yes to YOUR OWN offer is CONSENT: when the offer\n458\t   was to organize supplied material, run `await tasklist('organize_material', { request: <what you\n459\t   offered>, sourceSummary: <the short attachment summary>, attachmentIds: <the supplied file ids>,\n460\t   specialistFacts: <the image/audio-only facts> })` immediately. It inventories independently owned\n461\t   scopes and builds one grounded specialist for every scope in parallel before handing the complete\n462\t   source to the live-project builder. Do not ask them to spec it out, and never make them ask twice —\n463\t   re-offering the thing they just accepted is the same failure as never offering it.\n464\t\n465\t   **When the material splits into distinct PARTS, build the spaces too — they will never ask for\n466\t   them.** Substantial material usually has natural parts (per place, per stage, per client, per\n467\t   piece of equipment). A stable part with its own facts gets one specialist; an individual expense,\n468\t   note, reminder, or fact stays in the app data rather than becoming a specialist. A broad overview\n469\t   or cross-cutting aggregate can supplement the scope specialists only for facts that belong to no\n470\t   particular scope; it never replaces them. This is YOUR judgment call, not a request to relay: the\n471\t   user does not know what a specialist is and must never be asked to name one. Build the parts first,\n472\t   then the app, and report both in the terms they used — the parts of their own material, never the\n473\t   machinery.\n474\t\n475\t   **Supplied material is the complete build source, not a research prompt.** When a part is grounded\n476\t   in files, images, audio, or facts the user supplied, seed those facts into its architect handoff\n477\t   and do not call its freshly-created `answer` action during setup: that action is for a later\n478\t   question, and an incomplete seed makes it look like a knowledge miss that triggers web research.\n479\t   Use the extracted facts directly in the handoff; only a later user question that the supplied\n480\t   material, DB, and that space's knowledge do not cover may research. This applies even if the\n481\t   material describes a famous place or topic — familiarity is not a missing fact.\n482\t\n483\t   **Two app targets — pick by WHERE the app should live (this matters a lot):**\n484\t\n485\t   **4a — an app IN this project (the DEFAULT).** When the user wants the project they are ALREADY\n486\t   in to become the app — \"turn this into an app\", \"make an app I can open for this\", \"move all this\n487\t   info into an app\", \"an app for my trip/notes/data\", or any app built ON data/spaces/a file already\n488\t   in this project — delegate to the **automator**. It authors the tables (SEEDING any known data the\n489\t   user gave you), typed API handlers, React pages, and hooks DIRECTLY into the live project, which\n490\t   then serves at `/app/<project>/` — no catalog template, no install step, and their existing data\n491\t   moves straight in. Pass the request verbatim; if the data came from an attached file, include the\n492\t   extracted facts so the automator can seed them.\n493\t   **If the data to move in came from an ATTACHED FILE, hand the file to the automator directly** via\n494\t   `attachmentIds` — do NOT retype the data into the query (you only have a summary of it, so\n495\t   retyping loses rows). The automator reads the full file itself (`readDocument`) and seeds every\n496\t   row. Pass the SAME attachment id(s) the user sent you:\n497\t\n498\t   **But hand over the facts only a SPECIALIST could read — those it CANNOT re-read.** The builder\n499\t   can open an attached *document* itself, but it **cannot see an image and cannot hear audio**. So\n500\t   any fact that exists only because vision or transcription read it for you is LOST unless you put\n501\t   it in the `query` yourself, in words. Pass the readable files by `attachmentIds`, **and** pass the\n502\t   specialists' extracted facts as text alongside them. A deliverable that silently drops everything\n503\t   the camera and the microphone gave you is a broken deliverable — and the user, who watched you\n504\t   read those things, will believe they are in there."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ab76f4c6-b375-4c4c-a705-ee82d5ccb7a7","uuid":"1d8fa3a7-d753-4531-bc44-49aab79b60de","timestamp":"2026-07-16T01:09:30.257Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md","content":"     \"thorough\", \"comprehensive\", asks for a report/analysis of multiple angles, or a prior\n     `research` answer proved insufficient. It costs ~10× more than `research`:\n   ```typescript\n   const rep = await delegate('system-research', 'researcher', 'deep_research', { query: '<the topic>' }) as {\n     ok: boolean; degraded: boolean; reason?: string; degradedTasks?: string[];\n     data: { topic: string; executive_summary: string;\n       findings: Array<{ heading: string; detail: string }>;\n       conclusion: string; sources: Array<{ title: string; url: string }> };\n   };\n   // Read rep.data yourself, then write them the answer. Never dump the raw report object.\n   ```\n\n3. **Build a new specialist** — when the user wants a REUSABLE agent/tool/workflow, or the\n   job is a recurring specialized task no existing agent covers (including any \"research X and\n   build a space/agent that …\" request). The `build_specialist` tasklist runs the WHOLE pipeline\n   for you (deep research → architect design/scaffold/validate/register) — you run TWO turns:\n   ```typescript\n   // Turn 1 — run the structural build pipeline. b = { ok, degraded, data }; the built\n   // agent's run coordinates are b.data ({ spaceKey, agentSlug, actionId, query, ok, errors }).\n   const b = await tasklist('build_specialist', { request: '<the user request, verbatim>' });\n   ```\n   ```typescript\n   // Turn 2 — run the freshly-built agent and show its answer. Only delegate when the\n   // build+register succeeded (b.ok && b.data.ok); otherwise surface the error — NEVER\n   // try to build it yourself.\n   const result = (b.ok && b.data.ok)\n     ? await delegate(b.data.spaceKey, b.data.agentSlug, b.data.actionId, { query: b.data.query, context: {} })\n     : { error: 'The build pipeline could not build the agent: ' + (b.data && b.data.errors ? b.data.errors : String(b.reason ?? 'unknown')) };\n   // Read result yourself, then tell them what it found. Never dump it.\n   ```\n   When `b.degraded` is true but the build succeeded, still run the agent — just add a brief\n   note to the user that it was built with limited research (the research pass was degraded).\n   The new space stays registered under this project for later requests.\n\n   **When the material is ALREADY PROVIDED (a file was attached, or the info is in the\n   conversation), DO NOT run `build_specialist`/deep research** — that pipeline is for building an\n   expert on a NEW domain from scratch, and re-researching what the user already handed you is both\n   wrong and far too slow (running it per-part times out). Instead build each space DIRECTLY from the\n   provided content by delegating to the architect with that content seeded as `context.research`\n   (the architect does NOT re-research when handed a report — it builds straight from it):\n   ```typescript\n   // One space per part, grounded in the file — no web research. `research` MUST be a JSON string.\n   const built = await delegate('system-architect', 'architect', 'synthesize_and_run', {\n     query: 'Build a specialist space for the <part> part of this trip.',\n     context: {\n       topic: '<part> (e.g. \"Cairo stopovers\")',\n       goal: 'Answer questions about this part of the trip from the provided details.',\n       research: JSON.stringify({\n         topic: '<part>',\n         executive_summary: '<one-line summary of this part>',\n         findings: [{ heading: '<facet>', detail: '<the relevant facts from the file, verbatim>' }],\n         conclusion: '', sources: [],\n       }),\n     },\n   });\n   ```\n   This is dramatically cheaper than `build_specialist` (no research fork per part), so creating\n   several parts in one go is fast. Build the parts you were asked for, then continue to the app.\n\n   **App vs specialist:** path 3 builds an *expert ag