attachment flow stable across a fresh replay\n- R9 · step 1 · — · (no change) · verify=PASS · stable\n\n## step 2 — the bare \"yes\" → per-leg specialist spaces + DB + app, no research\nThe recurring hard one: THING builds FEWER specialists than the trip has legs, systematically\ndropping the MINOR legs (Cairo layover, Dar es Salaam transit) and keeping the salient ones\n(Serengeti/safari, Zanzibar), sometimes adding a generic catch-all.\n- R7 · step 2 · L1 · user-thing/thing/instruct.md (itinerary/destination scope prose) · verify=INTERRUPTED · **OVERFIT to the travel domain** (human de-overfit it to a domain-neutral \"brevity is not a merge\" rule; anti-overfitting rule in judge.md/scenario-spec.md hardened to forbid domain framing, not just literal tokens)\n- R8 · step 2 · L1 · user-thing/thing/instruct.md (domain-neutral \"scope-inventory rule\": complete inventory of independently-owned scopes; brevity is not a merge; an overview supplements, never replaces) + org/docs/system-spaces/README.md · verify=FAIL (2 clean reruns) · both persona replays still dropped Cairo AND Dar; a direct-authoring probe built all four → primitive is NOT the gap\n- **Escalation note (human, after R8):** two L1 rounds of the RIGHT prose have not moved it, and the\n  SAME two legs drop every time → this is SYSTEMATIC, not variance, and NOT an L1 problem. The\n  granularity is decided by how many parts THING enumerates before delegating (the architect builds\n  one space per seed — `system-architect/.../01-design.md` designs ONE agent per call). A free-form\n  judgment that must come out the same every time wants a **DETERMINISTIC L2 structure**: an\n  enumerate-then-`forEach` tasklist that lists the legs as discrete items and builds one specialist\n  per item, so \"how many specialists\" stops being a per-run dice roll. Next round: CLIMB to L2; do\n  not write the instruction a fourth time.\n- R9 · step 2 · **L2** · NEW `user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/` (01-inventory → 02-build_specialist `forEach` → 03-build_app) + instruct.md delegates to it + `libs/core/src/spaces/system-spaces-dag.test.ts` + org/docs · verify=**INCONCLUSIVE (ran out of context / runner timeout)** · **THE L2 FIX IS CORRECT AND WORKS FOR COVERAGE** — verify-rerun-3 built ALL FOUR legs (Cairo, Dar, safari, Zanzibar). It did NOT complete because the automator's app build then exceeded the runner's **10-min per-turn timeout**; the judge then hit \"Prompt is too long\" after 3 heavy reruns before writing a report. Inventory rule was iterated to its final form: READ the attached source docs before classifying scopes (earlier tries over-fragmented into facts, or missed legs).\n- **Direction (human, after R9):** DO NOT re-attribute and DO NOT rebuild `organize_material` — the L2\n  structure is right and already in the tree. The only reason step 2 didn't verify was the harness\n  per-turn timeout, now RAISED to 20 min (`sdk/org/scenarios/harness/lib/thing.mjs#dispatchAndWait`).\n  Round 10's job is narrow: rebuild, run ONE clean `--through 2` verify, confirm all four leg\n  specialists build ONCE each (no duplicate/overview catch-all) and the app builds, then judge step 2\n  PASS and continue to step 3+. Keep reruns to a MINIMUM (the build turn's trace is context-heavy —\n  don't burn context on repeats). If inventory still over/under-produces, tune ONLY 01-inventory's\n  rule; the structure stays.\n- R10 · step 2 · **L1 (architect action contract)** · `system-architect/agents/architect/instruct.md` (−12 net) + `libs/core/src/spaces/{prompt-contract,system-spaces-dag}.test.ts` · verify=**INCONCLUSIVE (ran out of context again)** · **DEEPER ROOT CAUSE found, past the L2 structure:** `organize_material`'s fan-out is WORKING — it enumerated all legs and fired all 5 architect delegates in parallel. But the architect's **action prompt manually CONTINUES after a tasklist result the runtime already auto-captures**; under the parallel `forEach`, that invalid cross-turn continuation clobbers sibling results → only the LAST architect build registers (some reruns instead over-produced 10 spaces w/ duplicate/overview junk — same bug, other face). R10 started the fix (delete the manual continuation, rely on the action runtime's envelope return) + updated both tests, but died of `Prompt is too long` before verifying.\n- **Context fix (human, after R10):** rounds 9 AND 10 both died of context exhaustion because\n  `step-NN.json` was an ~80KB full dump (every DB row + every yield's args) that the judge re-read\n  across reruns. FIXED: `run-yaml.mjs` now writes a ~10× smaller COMPACT `step-NN.json` (observables:\n  space names+count, table row-counts, delegate/yield kinds, errors, reply) and spills the raw dump to\n  `step-NN.full.json`; judge.md tells the judge to read compact by default. This should let a round\n  finish.\n- **Direction (human, after R10):** the architect action-contract fix is IN THE TREE (unverified). DO\n  NOT re-attribute — the diagnosis is solid (parallel architect results clobbered by the redundant\n  manual continuation). Rebuild, run ONE clean `--through 2` verify, and confirm ALL legs build ONCE\n  (no clobber → all present; no over-production → no duplicate/overview spaces). ⚠️ HIGH BLAST RADIUS:\n  the architect action contract drives EVERY space build product-wide — confirm the two updated tests\n  pass and that a SINGLE (non-parallel) `build_specialist` still returns its result. If verify is\n  green, step 2 is finally done → continue to step 3.\n- R11 · step 2 · (traced, no runtime edit) · verify=**INCONCLUSIVE (context death again)** · with R10's fix in the tree, step 2 swung the OTHER way: **17 fragmented spaces** (\"Cairo Stopover 1\", \"Cairo Stopover 1 Arrival\", \"Cairo Stopover 2\", \"Arusha Pre-Safari\", \"Arusha Post-Safari\", \"Suricata Booking\" + \"Suricata Circuit\", …) — the organizer RE-ENTERS / over-fragments. The judge was reaching for an **L3 action-runtime** change and died before writing it (no `src` runtime edit landed — the tree is still just the L2 tasklist + architect prompt + tests).\n- **ROOT CAUSE (human, after R11 — high confidence, verified by reading the prompt):** it is NOT an\n  L3 runtime bug. `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md` has **TWO overlapping build paths for supplied\n  material that both fire**: (1) path 3 (~L394–417) \"build each space DIRECTLY\" via an inline per-part\n  `delegate('system-architect','architect','synthesize_and_run')` loop, and (2) path 4a (~L458)\n  `tasklist('organize_material')` which ALREADY does inventory → per-scope specialist → app — AND THEN\n  (~L465–472) STILL says \"build the spaces too… Build the parts first, then the app\", duplicating what\n  organize_material just did. So THING runs organize_material AND the manual per-part build → double\n  build → re-entry / 17 fragments (and, when the manual path wins a race, the R10 clobber symptom).\n- **Direction (human, after R11):** make `organize_material` the SINGLE supplied-material build path.\n  In `thing/instruct.md`: on the \"supplied material + yes\" path, call `organize_material` and REPORT\n  its result — DELETE the competing manual per-part build guidance (the L465–472 \"build the parts\n  first, then the app\" prose, and steer path 3's inline `synthesize_and_run` loop to NON-supplied\n  single-space requests only). This is **L1**, one file, a deletion — do NOT touch the action runtime\n  (L3). Then RE-EXAMINE whether R10's architect continuation-removal is still needed with a single\n  path (it may have been chasing a symptom of the double-build; keep it only if a single-path verify\n  still shows a genuine parallel-clobber). Context death is fixed (compact `step-NN.json`), so ONE\n  clean `--through 2` verify should finish: expect ONE specialist per leg (Cairo, Dar, Zanzibar/Stone\n  Town, Serengeti/Ngorongoro safari), no duplicates, app served.\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":70,"oldLines":3,"newStart":70,"newLines":4,"lines":["   still shows a genuine parallel-clobber). Context death is fixed (compact `step-NN.json`), so ONE","   clean `--through 2` verify should finish: expect ONE specialist per leg (Cairo, Dar, Zanzibar/Stone","   Town, Serengeti/Ngorongoro safari), no duplicates, app served.","+- R12 · step 2 · L1 · `user-thing/thing#path-3-and-path-4-consent` + `organize_material/01-inventory` · verify=FAIL · organizer-only replay invoked the tasklist and built every required leg, but over-fragmented into 11 specialists and left `appManifest.built=false`; next round must diagnose tasklist inventory/app handoff rather than restoring duplicate direct calls."]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_a204b3d8-9692-44a0-9290-775a383a8783","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_er0Qcr8SP5LgYgRH5y0D9I4E","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/report.md","content":"# 06-tanzania — round 12 report\n\n## Verdict\n\n**Step 2 still fails; the L1 correction did not verify.** The initial clean replay (`attempt-2`) created the app data but **zero** specialist spaces because THING bypassed `organize_material` and called only `system-appbuilder/automator`. I changed the supplied-material consent path to make `organize_material` its only authoring call and reran from a fresh server through step 2 (`attempt-3`).\n\nThe rerun did invoke `organize_material` and produced all four required operational scopes, but it over-fragmented into **11** spaces and the compact state reported `appManifest.built: false`. The scenario requires exactly one specialist per leg and a served app with real pages, so this is an honest FAIL. No files were staged or committed.\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Attempt 2 — failure before the correction\n\n- `attempt-2/step-01.json` passed: it read all five attachments with `system-vision/vision`, `system-files/dispatch`, `reader`, and `sheet`; state remained empty and the reply offered an app.\n- `attempt-2/step-02.json` had a sole `system-appbuilder/automator` delegate, no tasklist yield, and no `system-architect` delegates.\n- Its state had five populated tables (`cost_items: 18`, `itinerary_legs: 8`, `loose_ends: 8`, `park_fees: 50`, `trip_notes: 32`) but `spaces: []`, `spaceCount: 0`, and `appManifest.built: false`.\n- The full evidence shows the appbuilder handoff directly: `delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', …)`. This contradicts the intended accepted-offer path and fails the first step-2 expectation independently of the otherwise useful seeded rows.\n\n### Attempt 3 — fresh verification after the correction\n\n- `attempt-3/run.log` confirms a clean pod root and `played 2/18 steps`.\n- `attempt-3/step-01.json` passed again: attachments were read, no authoring happened, and the reply offered an app.\n- `attempt-3/step-02.full.json` begins with `tasklist('organize_material', …)`, followed by four required architect delegates for Cairo, the northern safari circuit, Zanzibar, and Dar es Salaam. No web-search or web-fetch yield occurred.\n- However, `attempt-3/step-02.json` listed 11 registered spaces rather than the four scope specialists: `Egypt Cairo Stopovers`, `Safari Advisor`, `Zanzibar Trip Advisor`, `Dar City Stay`, plus `Arusha Safari Gateway`, `Flight Advisor`, `Travel Documents Advisor`, `Rock Restaurant Concierge`, `Ngorongoro Souvenir Memo`, `Traveler Profiles`, and `Trip Budget`.\n- The same compact state reported tables populated (`contacts: 4`, `cost_items: 20`, `itinerary_legs: 8`, `trip_notes: 2`, `trips: 1`) but `appManifest.built: false`. This disproves the served-app assertion.\n- Recovered typecheck errors during setup include implicit callback `any`, unfinished declarations, an unavailable `console`, and follow-up references to an unavailable `result`. They are not the primary first failure, but they likely contributed to the absent served manifest.\n\n## Attribution and changes\n\n### L1 — `sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`\n\n**Why this rung:** prior history proved that two free-form “make every part a specialist” instructions did not alter behavior, and R11 identified two competing paths. Attempt 2 confirmed the remaining problem exactly: THING skipped the existing `organize_material` DAG and directly invoked automator. The format already had the missing structure, so a framework change was neither needed nor justified.\n\n**Change:**\n\n- Limits the supplied-content shortcut in path 3 to a standalone specialist request, avoiding an implied second multi-scope path.\n- Replaces the accepted-offer prose with an explicit `tasklist('organize_material', …)` statement.\n- States that the organizer is the **only** authoring call; THING must not call the architect or automator before or after it.\n\n**General principle:** an orchestrator must choose one owning workflow for a compound operation. Once a workflow owns inventory, fan-out, and handoff, its caller must not repeat any stage independently; duplicate ownership creates races, omissions, and inconsistent output.\n\n**Verification:** the fresh replay proved the caller correction worked: it issued one organizer tasklist and the organizer fanned out the four required core scopes. It did **not** prove the full requirement because the organizer’s inventory remained too granular and the app was not marked built.\n\n### L1 — `sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/01-inventory.md`\n\nAfter the failed verification, I made a narrow, domain-neutral follow-up change to state the inventory’s intended partition explicitly: select the coarsest complete operational scopes; do not create a child scope whose facts and questions belong to its parent; do not split based only on different detail kinds. This is deliberately unverified in accordance with the one-failure-per-invocation rule.\n\n**Next diagnosis:** inspect the organizer’s app handoff and inventory output on a fresh replay. The remaining defect is now inside the L2 organizer structure: its enumeration should be constrained to a non-overlapping minimal partition, and the handoff needs to leave a served app manifest. Do not restore THING’s direct architect or automator calls.\n\n### Regression coverage — `sdk/org/libs/core/src/spaces/system.test.ts`\n\nUpdated the existing THING prompt contract to assert that an accepted supplied-material offer has one organizer-only authoring call, rather than expecting the removed free-form “build parts” sentence. I also made its multiline offer assertion whitespace-tolerant.\n\nTargeted tests passed:\n\n```text\nTest Files  3 passed (3)\nTests       37 passed (37)\n```\n\nThe test run retained two pre-existing warnings that automator’s instruction mentions `delegate()` while its frontmatter has `canDelegateTo: []`; the tests did not fail on those warnings.\n\n## Existing uncommitted changes retained\n\nThis round also relied on and left intact the previous uncommitted L2 organizer files, architect one-statement action contract, DAG/prompt tests, harness timeout increase, compact runner evidence, and matching documentation. I did not modify unrelated campaign artifacts or existing worktree changes.\n\n## Overfitting check\n\nI checked the product prompt/tasklist/test diff for scenario-specific names, fixture values, locations, people, booking references, and totals. The new rules describe only workflow ownership and a minimal non-overlapping partition; no scenario literal or scenario-domain instruction was introduced.\n\n## Artifact locations\n\n- Initial failure: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/attempt-2/{step-01,step-02}.{json,full.json}`\n- Fresh verification: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/attempt-3/{step-01,step-02}.{json,full.json}`\n- Progress log: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/PROGRESS.md`\n- Persistent attempt record: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/attempts/06-tanzania.md`\n"}}],"model":"gpt-5.6-terra","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ab76f4c6-b375-4c4c-a705-ee82d5ccb7a7","uuid":"259a5a9b-622c-4f3c-adc3-70a909f1d7d2"}
