{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_DR2g8sPpfgT2Uo4pZSeDTPWa","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# 06-tanzania — round 12 report\n2\t\n3\t## Verdict\n4\t\n5\t**Step 2 still fails; the L1 correction did not verify.** The initial clean replay (`attempt-2`) created the app data but **zero** specialist spaces because THING bypassed `organize_material` and called only `system-appbuilder/automator`. I changed the supplied-material consent path to make `organize_material` its only authoring call and reran from a fresh server through step 2 (`attempt-3`).\n6\t\n7\tThe rerun did invoke `organize_material` and produced all four required operational scopes, but it over-fragmented into **11** spaces and the compact state reported `appManifest.built: false`. The scenario requires exactly one specialist per leg and a served app with real pages, so this is an honest FAIL. No files were staged or committed.\n8\t\n9\t## Evidence\n10\t\n11\t### Attempt 2 — failure before the correction\n12\t\n13\t- `attempt-2/step-01.json` passed: it read all five attachments with `system-vision/vision`, `system-files/dispatch`, `reader`, and `sheet`; state remained empty and the reply offered an app.\n14\t- `attempt-2/step-02.json` had a sole `system-appbuilder/automator` delegate, no tasklist yield, and no `system-architect` delegates.\n15\t- Its state had five populated tables (`cost_items: 18`, `itinerary_legs: 8`, `loose_ends: 8`, `park_fees: 50`, `trip_notes: 32`) but `spaces: []`, `spaceCount: 0`, and `appManifest.built: false`.\n16\t- The full evidence shows the appbuilder handoff directly: `delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', …)`. This contradicts the intended accepted-offer path and fails the first step-2 expectation independently of the otherwise useful seeded rows.\n17\t\n18\t### Attempt 3 — fresh verification after the correction\n19\t\n20\t- `attempt-3/run.log` confirms a clean pod root and `played 2/18 steps`.\n21\t- `attempt-3/step-01.json` passed again: attachments were read, no authoring happened, and the reply offered an app.\n22\t- `attempt-3/step-02.full.json` begins with `tasklist('organize_material', …)`, followed by four required architect delegates for Cairo, the northern safari circuit, Zanzibar, and Dar es Salaam. No web-search or web-fetch yield occurred.\n23\t- However, `attempt-3/step-02.json` listed 11 registered spaces rather than the four scope specialists: `Egypt Cairo Stopovers`, `Safari Advisor`, `Zanzibar Trip Advisor`, `Dar City Stay`, plus `Arusha Safari Gateway`, `Flight Advisor`, `Travel Documents Advisor`, `Rock Restaurant Concierge`, `Ngorongoro Souvenir Memo`, `Traveler Profiles`, and `Trip Budget`.\n24\t- The same compact state reported tables populated (`contacts: 4`, `cost_items: 20`, `itinerary_legs: 8`, `trip_notes: 2`, `trips: 1`) but `appManifest.built: false`. This disproves the served-app assertion.\n25\t- Recovered typecheck errors during setup include implicit callback `any`, unfinished declarations, an unavailable `console`, and follow-up references to an unavailable `result`. They are not the primary first failure, but they likely contributed to the absent served manifest.\n26\t\n27\t## Attribution and changes\n28\t\n29\t### L1 — `sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`\n30\t\n31\t**Why this rung:** prior history proved that two free-form “make every part a specialist” instructions did not alter behavior, and R11 identified two competing paths. Attempt 2 confirmed the remaining problem exactly: THING skipped the existing `organize_material` DAG and directly invoked automator. The format already had the missing structure, so a framework change was neither needed nor justified.\n32\t\n33\t**Change:**\n34\t\n35\t- Limits the supplied-content shortcut in path 3 to a standalone specialist request, avoiding an implied second multi-scope path.\n36\t- Replaces the accepted-offer prose with an explicit `tasklist('organize_material', …)` statement.\n37\t- States that the organizer is the **only** authoring call; THING must not call the architect or automator before or after it.\n38\t\n39\t**General principle:** an orchestrator must choose one owning workflow for a compound operation. Once a workflow owns inventory, fan-out, and handoff, its caller must not repeat any stage independently; duplicate ownership creates races, omissions, and inconsistent output.\n40\t\n41\t**Verification:** the fresh replay proved the caller correction worked: it issued one organizer tasklist and the organizer fanned out the four required core scopes. It did **not** prove the full requirement because the organizer’s inventory remained too granular and the app was not marked built.\n42\t\n43\t### L1 — `sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/01-inventory.md`\n44\t\n45\tAfter the failed verification, I made a narrow, domain-neutral follow-up change to state the inventory’s intended partition explicitly: select the coarsest complete operational scopes; do not create a child scope whose facts and questions belong to its parent; do not split based only on different detail kinds. This is deliberately unverified in accordance with the one-failure-per-invocation rule.\n46\t\n47\t**Next diagnosis:** inspect the organizer’s app handoff and inventory output on a fresh replay. The remaining defect is now inside the L2 organizer structure: its enumeration should be constrained to a non-overlapping minimal partition, and the handoff needs to leave a served app manifest. Do not restore THING’s direct architect or automator calls.\n48\t\n49\t### Regression coverage — `sdk/org/libs/core/src/spaces/system.test.ts`\n50\t\n51\tUpdated the existing THING prompt contract to assert that an accepted supplied-material offer has one organizer-only authoring call, rather than expecting the removed free-form “build parts” sentence. I also made its multiline offer assertion whitespace-tolerant.\n52\t\n53\tTargeted tests passed:\n54\t\n55\t```text\n56\tTest Files  3 passed (3)\n57\tTests       37 passed (37)\n58\t```\n59\t\n60\tThe test run retained two pre-existing warnings that automator’s instruction mentions `delegate()` while its frontmatter has `canDelegateTo: []`; the tests did not fail on those warnings.\n61\t\n62\t## Existing uncommitted changes retained\n63\t\n64\tThis round also relied on and left intact the previous uncommitted L2 organizer files, architect one-statement action contract, DAG/prompt tests, harness timeout increase, compact runner evidence, and matching documentation. I did not modify unrelated campaign artifacts or existing worktree changes.\n65\t\n66\t## Overfitting check\n67\t\n68\tI checked the product prompt/tasklist/test diff for scenario-specific names, fixture values, locations, people, booking references, and totals. The new rules describe only workflow ownership and a minimal non-overlapping partition; no scenario literal or scenario-domain instruction was introduced.\n69\t\n70\t## Artifact locations\n71\t\n72\t- Initial failure: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/attempt-2/{step-01,step-02}.{json,full.json}`\n73\t- Fresh verification: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/attempt-3/{step-01,step-02}.{json,full.json}`\n74\t- Progress log: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/PROGRESS.md`\n75\t- Persistent attempt record: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/attempts/06-tanzania.md`\n76\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ab76f4c6-b375-4c4c-a705-ee82d5ccb7a7","uuid":"1ed8983b-de8a-450a-840e-e0cca6988fe2","timestamp":"2026-07-16T01:59:29.312Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/report.md","content":"# 06-tanzania — round 12 report\n\n## Verdict\n\n**Step 2 still fails; the L1 correction did not verify.** The initial clean replay (`attempt-2`) created the app data but **zero** specialist spaces because THING bypassed `organize_material` and called only `system-appbuilder/automator`. I changed the supplied-material consent path to make `organize_material` its only authoring call and reran from a fresh server through step 2 (`attempt-3`).\n\nThe rerun did invoke `organize_material` and produced all four required operational scopes, but it over-fragmented into **11** spaces and the compact state reported `appManifest.built: false`. The scenario requires exactly one specialist per leg and a served app with real pages, so this is an honest FAIL. No files were staged or committed.\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Attempt 2 — failure before the correction\n\n- `attempt-2/step-01.json` passed: it read all five attachments with `system-vision/vision`, `system-files/dispatch`, `reader`, and `sheet`; state remained empty and the reply offered an app.\n- `attempt-2/step-02.json` had a sole `system-appbuilder/automator` delegate, no tasklist yield, and no `system-architect` delegates.\n- Its state had five populated tables (`cost_items: 18`, `itinerary_legs: 8`, `loose_ends: 8`, `park_fees: 50`, `trip_notes: 32`) but `spaces: []`, `spaceCount: 0`, and `appManifest.built: false`.\n- The full evidence shows the appbuilder handoff directly: `delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', …)`. This contradicts the intended accepted-offer path and fails the first step-2 expectation independently of the otherwise useful seeded rows.\n\n### Attempt 3 — fresh verification after the correction\n\n- `attempt-3/run.log` confirms a clean pod root and `played 2/18 steps`.\n- `attempt-3/step-01.json` passed again: attachments were read, no authoring happened, and the reply offered an app.\n- `attempt-3/step-02.full.json` begins with `tasklist('organize_material', …)`, followed by four required architect delegates for Cairo, the northern safari circuit, Zanzibar, and Dar es Salaam. No web-search or web-fetch yield occurred.\n- However, `attempt-3/step-02.json` listed 11 registered spaces rather than the four scope specialists: `Egypt Cairo Stopovers`, `Safari Advisor`, `Zanzibar Trip Advisor`, `Dar City Stay`, plus `Arusha Safari Gateway`, `Flight Advisor`, `Travel Documents Advisor`, `Rock Restaurant Concierge`, `Ngorongoro Souvenir Memo`, `Traveler Profiles`, and `Trip Budget`.\n- The same compact state reported tables populated (`contacts: 4`, `cost_items: 20`, `itinerary_legs: 8`, `trip_notes: 2`, `trips: 1`) but `appManifest.built: false`. This disproves the served-app assertion.\n- Recovered typecheck errors during setup include implicit callback `any`, unfinished declarations, an unavailable `console`, and follow-up references to an unavailable `result`. They are not the primary first failure, but they likely contributed to the absent served manifest.\n\n## Attribution and changes\n\n### L1 — `sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`\n\n**Why this rung:** prior history proved that two free-form “make every part a specialist” instructions did not alter behavior, and R11 identified two competing paths. Attempt 2 confirmed the remaining problem exactly: THING skipped the existing `organize_material` DAG and directly invoked automator. The format already had the missing structure, so a framework change was neither needed nor justified.\n\n**Change:**\n\n- Limits the supplied-content shortcut in path 3 to a standalone specialist request, avoiding an implied second multi-scope path.\n- Replaces the accepted-offer prose with an explicit `tasklist('organize_material', …)` statement.\n- States that the organizer is the **only** authoring call; THING must not call the architect or automator before or after it.\n\n**General principle:** an orchestrator must choose one owning workflow for a compound operation. Once a workflow owns inventory, fan-out, and handoff, its caller must not repeat any stage independently; duplicate ownership creates races, omissions, and inconsistent output.\n\n**Verification:** the fresh replay proved the caller correction worked: it issued one organizer tasklist and the organizer fanned out the four required core scopes. It did **not** prove the full requirement because the organizer’s inventory remained too granular and the app was not marked built.\n\n### L1 — `sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/01-inventory.md`\n\nAfter the failed verification, I made a narrow, domain-neutral follow-up change to state the inventory’s intended partition explicitly: select the coarsest complete operational scopes; do not create a child scope whose facts and questions belong to its parent; do not split based only on different detail kinds. This is deliberately unverified in accordance with the one-failure-per-invocation rule.\n\n**Next diagnosis:** inspect the organizer’s app handoff and inventory output on a fresh replay. The remaining defect is now inside the L2 organizer structure: its enumeration should be constrained to a non-overlapping minimal partition, and the handoff needs to leave a served app manifest. Do not restore THING’s direct architect or automator calls.\n\n### Regression coverage — `sdk/org/libs/core/src/spaces/system.test.ts`\n\nUpdated the existing THING prompt contract to assert that an accepted supplied-material offer has one organizer-only authoring call, rather than expecting the removed free-form “build parts” sentence. I also made its multiline offer assertion whitespace-tolerant.\n\nTargeted tests passed:\n\n```text\nTest Files  3 passed (3)\nTests       37 passed (37)\n```\n\nThe test run retained two pre-existing warnings that automator’s instruction mentions `delegate()` while its frontmatter has `canDelegateTo: []`; the tests did not fail on those warnings.\n\n## Existing uncommitted changes retained\n\nThis round also relied on and left intact the previous uncommitted L2 organizer files, architect one-statement action contract, DAG/prompt tests, harness timeout increase, compact runner evidence, and matching documentation. I did not modify unrelated campaign artifacts or existing worktree changes.\n\n## Overfitting check\n\nI checked the product prompt/tasklist/test diff for scenario-specific names, fixture values, locations, people, booking references, and totals. The new rules describe only workflow ownership and a minimal non-overlapping partition; no scenario literal or scenario-domain instruction was introduced.\n\n## Artifact locations\n\n- Initial failure: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/attempt-2/{step-01,step-02}.{json,full.json}`\n- Fresh verification: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/attempt-3/{step-01,step-02}.{json,full.json}`\n- Progress log: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/12/06-tanzania/PROGRESS.md`\n- Persistent attempt record: `automation/instances/scenario-campaign/attempts/06-tanzania.md`\n","numLines":76,"startLine":1,"totalLines":76}}}
